explanation:
For deciding whether any statements in OS_DoTimerAdd are dead code we must know which operations have observable side effects (so cannot be removed) and which are pure/no-op. The following symbols are required and why:

- OS_CHECK_POINTER
  - These macro(s) validate pointers at function start and likely perform early-return or logging. Need their definition to know if the initial checks can return (control-flow) or produce side effects (e.g. call OS_printf) so that the presence/absence of those checks would affect behaviour.

- OS_CHECK_APINAME
  - Same as above; this macro checks timer_name. Its expansion determines control-flow and side-effects.

- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET
  - Macro used to get a pointer to the object table entry. Must know whether it merely computes an address (no side-effect) or has additional semantics (e.g. memory fences, checks) that make the assignment using its result necessary.

- OS_OBJECT_INIT
  - Macro used to initialize the new timecb object entry and save the name. Its expansion may perform non-trivial initialization (writes, sequence numbers, side-effects) so it cannot be assumed dead without seeing it.

- OS_timecb_table
  - Global table referenced by OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET; need its declaration/layout to determine whether reading/writing through it has side-effects or whether some assignments are redundant.

- OS_timebase_table
  - Global table for timebase objects. Required to know initial values (e.g. first_cb) and whether accesses/updates (timebase->first_cb) are observable.

- OS_timecb_internal_record_t
  - Definition of the time callback record (fields used: timebase_token, callback_ptr, callback_arg, flags, prev_cb, next_cb). Needed to know which writes in OS_DoTimerAdd mutate observable state and which might be unused/overwritten later (dead assignments).

- OS_timebase_internal_record_t
  - Definition of the timebase record (field used: first_cb and possibly locking/metadata). Needed to determine whether modifying first_cb is observable or redundant.

- OS_object_token_t
  - Token type semantics (size, contents) are needed because tokens are transferred/initialized/converted; this determines whether token assignments/transfer operations are observable.

- osal_id_t
  - Type of timer_id and id fields; required to understand conversions, identity values and whether some assignments are no-op.

- OS_ArgCallback_t
  - Callback function pointer type to know if storing callback_ptr into the record has any special semantic (e.g. wrapper generation) or if it’s purely a pointer assignment.

- OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_TIMEBASE
  - Constant used in type checks. Needed to determine the branch that returns OS_ERR_INCORRECT_OBJ_STATE and whether that branch is reachable in typical configurations.

- OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_TIMECB
  - Constant used when allocating and getting timecb objects; affects which object table and initialization occur — needed to reason about observable effects of allocation and subsequent assignments.

- OS_SUCCESS
  - Return-code constant used to gate much of the function. Knowing its exact value is necessary to interpret conditional branches and whether certain code blocks are reachable.

- OS_ERR_INCORRECT_OBJ_STATE
  - Specific error returned if called from a timebase callback. Required to decide if that early return is possible and thus whether subsequent code could be dead in some configurations.

- OS_LOCK_MODE_REFCOUNT
  - Lock mode passed to OS_ObjectIdGetById; its semantics (e.g. increments refcount vs not) determine whether the call has observable side-effects that prevent it being removed.

- OS_LOCK_MODE_NONE
  - Lock mode used when reading the callback ring; needed to reason about the success/failure of OS_ObjectIdGetById calls and whether the conditional insertion code is required or could be eliminated.

Note: many functions called by OS_DoTimerAdd (OS_ObjectIdGetById, OS_ObjectIdAllocateNew, OS_ObjectIdTransferToken, OS_ObjectIdFromToken, OS_TimeBaseLock_Impl, OS_TimeBaseUnlock_Impl, OS_ObjectIdFinalizeNew, OS_ObjectIdRelease) are present in the static call graph; their presence is necessary but they are already known. The symbols above are additional, not listed in the graph, and are required specifically to determine whether the assignments/initializations and the control-flow in OS_DoTimerAdd produce observable effects (and therefore are not dead code).
